The target Crown enables the uniform release of gas as the bullet exits the barrel, preventing a shift in trajectory. The Crown is recessed to protect it from accidental damage that degrades accuracy. Free floated barrel eliminates contact interference from the fore-end, enabling the superior barrel craftsmanship to perform consistently and accurately. Adjustable Feather Trigger minimizes the "human factor" by eliminating creep and take-up — providing a crisp trigger pull that "breaks like glass." Low profile action allows you to mount the scope extremely close to the center of the bore to minimize the offset between point of aim and Point of Impact. 60° bolt lift keeps the thumb and fingers clear of the scope when cycling the action and allows the bolt to be operated in a smoother/quicker motion. Top-tang safety offers easy accessibility without removing your firing hand from the stock. The shooter can quickly manipulate the safety, or verify the position of the safety, without losing your sight picture or cheek weld. Detachable Rotary magazine is built from tough polymer and is designed to stop forward movement of the cartridge by contacting the shoulder of the case rather than the tip of the projectile. This prevents bullet tip deformation and recoil induced bullet seating depth change. Bolt Unlock Button allows the bolt to be cycled with the safety engaged. title: For Sale:  1928 Tula hex receiver Mosin Nagant M91-30 ex dragoon excellent condition
postcontent:
For sale is a very collectible version of the Mosin Nagant M91-30, it is a 1928 Tula hex receiver ex-dragoon. The barrel, receiver, bolt, and butt plate match. The floor plate of the magazine has been force matched at the arsenal. This version of the rifle is highly coveted for its unique barrel markings (translated as Foremost Ordnance Factory of the USSR at Tula) and the hex receivers are sought after for higher level of quality control during this manufacturing period. In addition. this rifle has the sought after brass cap upper handguards, a matching original sling with hammer and sickle markings, and a very unique appearing stock. The stock is in excellent condition with no cracks or warps. It has been expertly restored and does not have a drop of cosmoline on it. It does not have any rust. It has been sighted in via iron sights at 50 yards and shoots fantastically. The bolt is smooth, and the barrel has strong rifling without being counterbored. This rifle is both a great shooter and very collectable. With the ban on Russian imports, Mosin Nagant rifles have become harder and harder to locate!

$250 for the rifle plus a sling, bayonet, oil can, and tools. Price is open to negotiation if you are also interested in purchasing ammunition. I can include as much 7.62x54r surplus ammunition as you desire for a price. Transaction to be done at a local FFL here in Syracuse. I will consider shipping but only if shipping costs are covered by the buyer.

Call or text 3-one-5 two-5-six 3-6-seven-four if you are interested, have any questions, or need additional pictures.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Springfield FAL - metric, .308, match barrel.
postcontent:
Armslist only allows me to upload one photo. More photographs available on request to serious buyers!

Unfortunately, "fun money" is tight right now, and if I want a new toy, I have to get rid of one.

This is a rare bird - a metric FAL made for Springfield under contract by Imbel on the original Belgian tooling, with a Springfield match grade barrel rather than the original mil spec.

The log book shows approximately 300 rounds through it. The gun is in overall excellent condition, with little to no wear on the internals, a mirror bore, and only handling marks on the exterior - NRA "Excellent" condition or better, if you're familiar with that grading system.

They were brought in in a few configurations over the years; this is one of the later models that were caught in limbo during the Federal AWB in 1994. Very few made it into the country.

I'm the second owner, having purchased it from a friend in 2008. The only modification to the rifle is the removal of the original thumbhole stock, and the addition of a receiver mounted rail - itself extremely hard to find these days, as the company that made them no longer exists, and the mounts themselves haven't been available in years.

The rifle comes with a hard case and three 20 round magazines. One of them is pretty banged up. If you really want it, I can also throw in a cheapie adjustable scope.

I'm only interested in some very specific trades - I'm looking for either:
- a complete A3 upper including BCG, plus the difference in cash or a nice piece of glass;
- or a straight across swap for an LE6920.

title: For Sale:  PPS43C 7.62x25 w/300 rounds ammo
postcontent:
PPs43-C pistol in caliber 7.62x25. This pistol is manufactured at the famed Radom Plant in Poland. All parts and components were new and Polish made.
Gently used and like new... 200-300 rounds at slow fire range only. 
Comes with 4 magazines, magazine pouch for 3 mags, original style leather/webbing sling, cleaning rod, oil can and hardcase.  PLUS 300 rounds of new clean ammo.   $500.00                                                                  
The folding stock is not functional. The mechanism is disabled and it has been welded in place
Face to face, cash only sale, must show proof of age - Driver's License

The History... The PPS-43C (Pistolet-Pulemet Sudaeva, model of 1943 = Sudaev SMG) was born as an answer to the need for a weapon that is more compact and mobile than the PPSh-41, then in use by the Soviet Army. The PPSh-41 was somewhat too long to be used by tank crews and mobile recon groups and paratroopers, so late in 1941, the Red Army issued a request for a new more compact sub machine gun (SMG). The designer Sudaev initially designed his new SMG in 1942, and it was adopted under the designation of PPS-42. The next year he refined the design, and this final model was designated as the PPS-43. This model was manufactured in significant numbers (nearly two million PPS-43 weapons were manufactured between 1943 and 1946). The PPS-43 is sometimes referred to as the best SMG of World War II. After WWII, it was widely exported to pro-Soviet regimes around the world, and widely copied.
Today...I.O. Inc. redesigned this historical firearm to shoot from a closed bolt position. The safety is located at the front of the triggerguard. The receiver and barrel shroud are made from stamped steel. The rear sight is an L-shaped flip type and is marked for 100 and 200 meters, the front sight is a fixed blade type. The barrel is equipped with a simple muzzle brake. This firearm is an ATF approved pistol. The stock has no function and is permanently fixed in its folded position.
